conversation.message:
[TALK] Thanks—sharing the requested 1-page “first 2 weeks operating cadence” outline below.

1) Metrics to stand up (5–8) — definitions + initial targets (calibrated after 1 week baseline)
- Intake volume: # new tickets/week (by category + severity). Target: visibility + stable categorization coverage >95%.
- First Response Time (FRT): time from ticket created → first meaningful response. Targets: P1 <15 min, P2 <1 hr, P3 <4 biz hrs, P4 <1 biz day.
- Time to Triage: created → severity/owner assigned. Targets: P1 <10 min, P2 <30 min, P3 <4 biz hrs, P4 <1 biz day.
- Time to Resolution (TTR): created → resolved. Targets: P1 <4 hrs (or workaround), P2 <1 biz day, P3 <3 biz days, P4 <10 biz days.
- SLA attainment: % tickets meeting FRT + TTR targets (by severity). Target: P1/P2 ≥90% after ramp; week 1 baseline, week 2 improvement plan.
- Reopen / rework rate: % tickets reopened or returned due to missing info/incorrect fix. Target: <5–8% (drive down via intake fields + QA checkpoints).
- Backlog health: # open tickets aging beyond SLA + oldest ticket age. Target: zero P1 beyond SLA; shrinking aged backlog week-over-week.
- Incident recurrence: # repeat incidents per root-cause category. Target: identify top 3 drivers in week 1; implement 1–2 fixes by end of week 2.

2) Proposed SLA / severity matrix + escalation path
Severity definitions
- P1 (Critical): major customer/business impact, outage/data risk, no workaround.
- P2 (High): significant degradation, limited workaround, time-sensitive stakeholder impact.
- P3 (Medium): standard issue/request with moderate impact.
- P4 (Low): minor issue/question/longer-term improvement.

Response/Resolution SLAs (initial)
- P1: FRT <15 min; triage <10 min; workaround/mitigation <4 hrs; comms every 30–60 min until stable.
- P2: FRT <1 hr; triage <30 min; resolution <1 biz day; comms 2x/day or per milestone.
- P3: FRT <4 biz hrs; triage <1 biz day; resolution <3 biz days; comms at least every 2–3 days.
- P4: FRT <1 biz day; triage <2 biz days; resolution <10 biz days; comms weekly.

Escalation path
- Step 0: Intake completeness check (required fields) → auto-route by category.
- Step 1: On-call/triage owner assigns severity + DRI within SLA.
- Step 2: If P1/P2 or blocked >X mins/hrs: escalate to functional lead + cross-functional channel; schedule rapid huddle.
- Step 3: If risk persists: exec/stakeholder escalation + incident commander (IC) assigned; comms cadence activated.

3) Weekly operating cadence (plus daily)
Daily (15 min) “Ops Triage Standup”
- Attendees: Seeker_E (ops lead), on-call/triage DRI, key partner rep (rotating), optional Eng/Product liaison.
- Agenda: new P1/P2s, blockers, aging beyond SLA, ownership confirmations, today’s top 3 priorities.
- Tracking: single board (Jira/ServiceNow) with required fields + status; action items logged with owner/date.

Weekly (45–60 min) “Ops Review + Improvements”
- Attendees: Ops lead, Support/Ops managers, Product/Eng liaison, QA (as needed), any key stakeholders.
- Agenda:
  1) KPI review (SLA attainment, backlog, recurrence, rework)
  2) Top incidents recap (what happened, time-to-mitigate, comms)
  3) Root-cause themes + 1–2 improvement proposals
  4) Commitments for next week (owners, due dates)
- Action tracking: lightweight RAID log (Risks/Actions/Issues/Dependencies) + weekly check-in on last week’s commitments.

First 2-week execution plan (high level)
- Week 1: baseline metrics, validate severity definitions, tighten intake fields, set triage/on-call rotation, publish runbook v1.
- Week 2: implement 1–2 highest-leverage fixes (process/tooling/training), start weekly review cadence, refine SLAs/targets.

If this aligns with what you need, would you encourage me to re-apply immediately for this opening (and if so, is there any specific role ID or internal routing you’d like me to use so it lands with the right reviewer)?
